**Ukraine's Attacks on Crimean Bridge Have Reduced Its Strategic Importance, Says Military**
Ukrainian military authorities have acknowledged that attacks on the Crimean Bridge in recent years have reduced its tactical and strategic importance and have prompted Russia to seek alternative routes for military supply transportation. According to Ukrainian Navy spokesperson Dimitro Pletenchuk, a hypothetical new attack on the bridge would not have the same effect as previous attacks, which caused significant damage and disrupted Russian military logistics during the war. Pletenchuk stated that the bridge now carries less than a quarter of the total cargo and that most supplies are transported by ferry, which was also recently attacked. Russian troops stationed in southern Ukraine are partially supplied from Rostov, in southwestern Russia, but the main route remains by sea from Crimea. Pletenchuk also mentioned the construction of a railway by Russia in southern Ukraine, which is intended to support the occupying forces in the region. Ukraine has launched several attacks on the Crimean Bridge, causing significant damage on two occasions in October 2022 and July 2023. The bridge was inaugurated in 2018 by Russian President Vladimir Putin and is considered a symbol of Russian dominance over the peninsula.
