**Crimean Bridge: Ukraine's Most Successful Operation Against Russia**
Eugene Dykyi, a veteran of the Russian-Ukrainian war, told 24 Channel that the attacks on Crimea can be considered the most successful strategic operation of Ukraine, which has been ongoing for over a month. The enemy has not adapted to these attacks. The operation involves all branches of the military, with the Main Intelligence Directorate playing the leading role. This is a big operation, and it's fully justified. We're opening up the sky, and as a lure, we're using the Crimean Bridge. Note that we're not hitting the bridge itself, but the enemy is so attached to it that they're trying to cover it with powerful air defense systems. We're not touching the bridge, but we're destroying the air defense systems, said Dykyi. The occupiers are forced to use air defense systems from different parts of Russia. There was information as early as 2023 that the invaders brought air defense systems from the Arctic and the Far East. The situation is very interesting, as it turns out that the occupiers can only cover the front line, Moscow, and the Crimean Bridge. Therefore, Russia lacks surface-to-air missile systems to cover airfields with strategic bombers, oil refineries, and other military objects. This strategic operation has two components: the relocation of air defense systems in Crimea and deep, long-range strikes on the occupiers' airfields and oil refineries. This is currently the most successful thing we've done in the last year, emphasized Dykyi. These strikes can also be considered a certain preparation for the appearance of F-16 fighters in Ukraine. It will be much easier to work on Russian aircraft if the occupiers do not have an echeloned air defense system. Ukraine regularly destroys military objects and equipment of the occupiers in Crimea. For example, on the night of June 12, it was possible to destroy two S-300 complexes and hit S-400. It is known that Ukraine has found an alternative to Starlink systems for strikes on Crimea. Negotiations are currently underway. Previously, media published satellite images of the strike on the S-400 air defense system in Crimea.
